  <note>
    <title>Major Salivary Gland Tumor</title>
    <created>20230705T102847Z</created>
    <updated>20251226T063127Z</updated>
    <note-attributes>
      <author>Elaine huang</author>
    </note-attributes>
    <content>
      <![CDATA[<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" standalone="no"?>
<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Microscopic description:</div><div>Histologic Type: </div><div>Tumor size: </div><div>Histologic grade: Not applicable  / Low / Intermediate / High / High-grade transformation / Cannot be assessed </div><div>+Macroscopic tumor extent:</div><div>Lymphatic and / or Vascular Invasion: Not identified / Present</div><div>Perineural Invasion: Not identified / Present, intratumoral / extratumoral / intraneural</div><div>Margins:</div><div>  All margins negative for carcinoma.</div><div>  Distance from invasive tumor to closest margin: _ cm</div><div>Reiongal lymph node status: Not applicable</div><div>  _/_</div><div>  Size of largest nodal metastatic deposit</div><div>  Extranodal Extension (ENE): Not identified / Present</div><div>Distant metastasis: Not applicable</div><div>pTNM: pT___ (AJCC 8th Edition) </div><div>TNM descrptor: ____</div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div><br/></div><div>*Grade: </div><div><span style="color:rgb(26, 169, 178);">The classic categories that are still graded using three tier schemes include mucoepidermoid carcinoma, and carcinoma, not otherwise specified. While adenoid cystic carcinoma was historically stratified into three tiers, current classification no longer advocates for this.</span></div><div><span style="color:rgb(26, 169, 178);">Additionally, several tumor types can at least be stratified into low and high grade. High grade transformation (historically designated as dedifferentiation)</span></div><div><span style="color:rgb(26, 169, 178);">refers to the phenomenon of progression from a conventional, usually indolent phenotype, to a pleomorphic aggressive morphology</span></div></en-note>      ]]>
    </content>
  </note>
  <note>
    <title>Modified Weiss</title>
    <created>20160211T054025Z</created>
    <updated>20161201T151613Z</updated>
